\details{
Internal Delta construction and projection helpers

Developer-facing documentation for the helpers that convert joint component
effects into the derived combined-outcome contrast \code{Delta} and project the
joint confidence region onto that scale.
\subsection{\code{delta_na_interval()}}{

Returns the package-wide missing-value interval placeholder \code{c(NA, NA)}. Its
role is purely structural: all unsupported or failed \code{Delta} interval slots
use the same sentinel shape.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_from_components(atom, mu0, mu1, pi0, pi1)}}{

Computes the derived combined-outcome mean difference from arm-specific
observed-outcome means (\code{mu0}, \code{mu1}), observation probabilities (\code{pi0},
\code{pi1}), and the atom value. The helper returns a scalar numeric \code{Delta}. Its
role is to encode the defining transformation used everywhere in the package.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_welch_interval(y, r, conf.level)}}{

Builds the descriptive raw-scale \code{Delta} Welch interval by treating the
combined outcome \code{y} as a standard two-sample mean problem split by treatment
indicator \code{r}. It returns a length-two numeric interval and falls back to a
point-mass interval when the pooled standard error is not usable. Its role is
to provide the model-light \code{Delta} interval returned by
\code{confint(..., parameter = "delta", method = "welch")}.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_unadjusted_point_estimate(object, tol = 1e-8)}}{

Reconstructs the fitted \code{Delta} point estimate for an unadjusted successful
object. For the semi-parametric method it first solves the empirical-
likelihood nuisance location so the arm-specific observed means are coherent
with the fitted mean difference; otherwise it uses the raw observed means. It
returns a scalar numeric value. Its role is to populate \code{object$delta} in a
way that matches the fitted method.
}

\subsection{\code{prepareParametricJointReference(data, atom)} and}{

\code{prepareSPLRTJointReference(data, atom)}

Build cached reference objects for the parametric and semi-parametric joint
candidate evaluators. \code{data} is the standardized analysis frame and \code{atom} is
the fitted atom value. Each helper returns a list containing the cached model
fits or empirical-likelihood ingredients required for repeated candidate
evaluation. Their role is to avoid refitting the expensive shared pieces at
every surface or optimization step.
}

\subsection{`parametricJointCandidate(parametricReference, muDelta, logORdelta,}{

tol = 1e-12)`

Evaluates a constrained parametric candidate at fixed component effects. The
helper fits offset logistic and linear models, returns the Bernoulli and
Normal likelihood-ratio contributions, arm-specific parameters, the implied
\code{Delta}, and the constrained models themselves. Infeasible constrained fits
yield \code{Inf} components or \code{NA} parameters. Its role is to provide the core
parametric candidate object used by simultaneous-region and \code{Delta}
calculations.
}

\subsection{\code{splrtContinuousCandidate(splrtReference, muDelta, p0, p1, tol = 1e-8)}}{

Evaluates the continuous empirical-likelihood component of the semi-
parametric candidate given a proposed observed-outcome mean difference
\code{muDelta} and arm-specific observation probabilities \code{p0} and \code{p1}. The
helper returns feasibility, the continuous likelihood-ratio statistic, the
implied arm-specific means, and the resulting \code{Delta}. Its role is to isolate
the continuous half of the semi-parametric joint candidate.
}

\subsection{\code{splrtJointCandidate(splrtReference, muDelta, logORdelta, tol = 1e-8)}}{

Combines the profiled logistic candidate with the empirical-likelihood
continuous candidate for a semi-parametric joint evaluation. The helper
returns the total statistic, component contributions, arm-specific
probabilities and means, and the implied \code{Delta}. It truncates very small
negative totals to zero. Its role is the semi-parametric analogue of
\code{parametricJointCandidate()}.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_projection_candidate_factory(object)}}{

Chooses the appropriate candidate generator for the fitted method stored in
\code{object}. It returns a closure taking \verb{(muDelta, logORdelta)} and producing a
joint candidate object. It errors for adjusted fits and unsupported methods.
Its role is to hide the parametric versus semi-parametric branching from the
projection optimizer.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_projection_penalty_scale(object)}}{

Derives a scale factor used to penalize infeasible candidates during the
constrained projection optimization. The helper returns a positive scalar
based on the observed range of \code{Y}, defaulting safely to \code{1}. Its role is to
make the optimizer strongly prefer feasible points without being completely
detached from the scale of the outcome.
}

\subsection{\code{delta_projection_center(object, bounds)} and}{

\code{delta_projection_start_points(object, bounds)}

\code{delta_projection_center()} returns the preferred central point in the search
box, using the fitted component estimates when finite and falling back to the
midpoint of \code{bounds}. \code{delta_projection_start_points()} expands that center
into a deduplicated set of corner and midpoint starting values. Their role is
to seed the optimizer from several plausible locations so the projection
search is less sensitive to local numerical issues.
}

